Surrey, England":"Limpsfield, Surrey, England","Salem, Essex, Massachusetts Bay Colony, British Colonial America":"Salem, Essex, Massachusetts Bay Colony, British Colonial America","Broadwindsor, Dorset, England":"Broadwindsor, Dorset, England","Leicester, Leicestershire, England":"Leicester, Leicestershire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Alis","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"Alice","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."]},{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705210,"age":10,"year":"1600","julianDay":2305448,"title":"The Honourable East India Company","description":"The Honourable East India Company, a British joint-stock company, was established in 1600 for trade in the Indian Ocean region. At its height, the British East India Company had a private army which was twice the size of the British Army, ruled large sections of India, and revenues in the millions.","url":"https://www.historic-uk.com/HistoryUK/HistoryofEngland/The-East-India-Company/","urlTitle":"Historic UK - The East India Company","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705212,"age":30,"year":"1620","julianDay":2312753,"title":"The Pilgrims Board the Mayflower","description":"\"The Pilgrims boarded the Mayflower in search of religious freedom in the New World in September 1620. The Mayflower set sail from Plymouth, England, with 102 passengers, 40 of whom called themselves \"\"Saints.\"\" After two stormy months at sea, the ship reached the New World. Nearly half of the group died during their first winter due to malnutrition and the harsh New England winter.\"","url":"https://www.themayflowersociety.org/the-pilgrims/pilgrim-history","urlTitle":"The Mayflower Society - Pilgrim History","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705213,"age":52,"year":"1642","toYear":"1651","julianDay":2320789,"title":"The English Civil War","description":"A series of conflicts regarding England's governance during the years 1642 to 1651 is now known as The English Civil War. Charles I summoned supporters to join him against his enemies in Parliament. In October 1642, nearly 10,000 men fought for Charles I and chased Parliament across the River Tamar. Fighting continued for years and was finally ended at the Battle of Worcester on September 3, 1651, with a Parliamentarian victory.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Alis was born in 1590, in Limpsfield, Surrey, England. She married Hugh Laskin in 1610, in Leicester, Leicestershire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. She died on 28 July 1658, in Salem, Essex, Massachusetts Bay Colony, British Colonial America, at the age of 68, and was buried in Salem, Essex, Massachusetts Bay Colony, British Colonial America."},"et":{"1590–28 July 1658":"1590–28. juuli 1658","1587–1659":"1587–1659","–Male":"Surnud","1614–1677":"1614–1677","1615–Male":"1615–Surnud","1590–1658":"1590–1658","1590":"1590","about 1615":"umbes 1615","1600":"1600","1677":"1677","1610":"1610","1642":"1642","1620":"1620","1587":"1587","1651":"1651","28 July 1658":"28. juuli 1658","1615":"1615","1659":"1659","1614":"1614","1658":"1658",",, England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Limpsfield, Surrey, England":"Limpsfield, Surrey, England","Salem, Essex, Massachusetts Bay Colony, British Colonial America":"Salem, Essex, Massachusetts